results.name: Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct positive numbers such that for any prime p, any run of consecutive multiples of p has length exactly 3.
comment: If a prime p divides a(n), then there is a run of exactly three terms (one of which is a(n)) that are divisible by p.
If "three" is changed to "two", we get A280864.
Conjecture: This is a permutation of the positive integers.
link: Rémy Sigrist, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..20000
Rémy Sigrist, PARI program for A338338
example: After 1,2,4,6,3, we have had two successive multiples of 3, so the next term must be a multiple of 3 we have not yet seen, hence 9. The following term is then the smallest number not yet seen which is not a multiple of 3, hence 5.
xref: A338339-A338349, A338440, A338449, A338450, and A338451 analyze this sequence from various points of view.
